     <LINES>
      <TLINE>
       <TDFORMAT>U1</TDFORMAT>
       <TDLINE>&amp;PURPOSE&amp;</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDFORMAT>AS</TDFORMAT>
       <TDLINE>The material price variance report allows the user to compare material</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>prices.  This is especially useful in advanced inventory analysis where</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>large price differences exist between plants for the same material (e.g.</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>old low-priced stock in Plant A versus new higher-priced stock in Plant</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>B).</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDFORMAT>AS</TDFORMAT>
       <TDLINE>The original data is at the material/company/plant level.  All SAP price</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>data is also at this level.  The report also displays a calculated</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>average price, minimum price, maximum price, price variance, average</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>price value and stock variance.   The data comes from the SAP tables</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>MARA, MARC, MARD &amp; MBEW.</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDFORMAT>AS</TDFORMAT>
       <TDLINE>ABAP Program: ZMMR_MATERIAL_PRICE_VARIANCE</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDFORMAT>AS</TDFORMAT>
       <TDLINE>Transaction Code: ZMM_PRICE_VAR</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDFORMAT>U1</TDFORMAT>
       <TDLINE>&amp;INTEGRATION&amp;</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDFORMAT>AS</TDFORMAT>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDFORMAT>U1</TDFORMAT>
       <TDLINE>&amp;PREREQUISITES&amp;</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDFORMAT>AS</TDFORMAT>
       <TDLINE>Company code allows the user to group all the plants attached to one</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>company code.  The prices are separated at the material level first,</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>then company code level and then plant level. (The separation by company</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>code is generated by using table T001K and is created by the program ).</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDFORMAT>AS</TDFORMAT>
       <TDLINE>The average price calculation is the average of all the prices across</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>the plants, per company, per material. If the report is summarized to</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>the company level, the average is for each company.  The minimum price</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>and maximum price fields work the same way.</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDFORMAT>U1</TDFORMAT>
       <TDLINE>&amp;FEATURES&amp;</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDFORMAT>AS</TDFORMAT>
       <TDLINE>The average price may be calculated in 3 different ways.   (1)</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>Combination, (2) Total Dollars / Total QOH (is a &quot;Weighted Average&quot;</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>calculation), or (3) Sum Prices / Count Prices (is a &quot;Simple Average&quot;</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>calculation).  The Combination approach is the recommended method</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>because it best considers zero QOH measures.  The explanation of</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>formulas in their reverse order provides the easiest understanding: (3)</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>Simple Average Price = [SUM of applicable plant Prices] divided by</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>[COUNT of applicable plant Prices], (2) Weighted Average Price = [SUM of</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>(Price * QOH) for applicable plants] divided by [SUM of QOH for</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>applicable plants], (1) Combination = if Total QOH &gt; 0 then use Weighted</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>Average formula else if Total QOH = 0 then use Simple Average Price</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>formula.</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDFORMAT>AS</TDFORMAT>
       <TDLINE>Report data may be summarized in 3 different ways.  (1)</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>Material/Company/Plant, (2) Material &amp; Company, or (3) Material.</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE> It is important to remember that when Material/Company/Plant is</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>selected and multiple company codes are queried, then the Average Price</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>calculation is calculated at the individual company code level.</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDFORMAT>AS</TDFORMAT>
       <TDLINE>There are also options to suppress (not include) prices when the</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>quantity is zero or the plant price is marked for deletion or the</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>material is marked for deletion.  (Note: Spectra East &quot;Plant Price Is</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>Flagged For Deletion&quot; is configured to be identical to &quot;Plant Is Flagged</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>For Deletion&quot;.)</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDFORMAT>AS</TDFORMAT>
       <TDLINE>If the report is at the plant level, the user has several options to</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>limit the report using the price variance and stock  variances.  The</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>PRICE VARIANCE VALUE +- can be used to remove materials where the price</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>variance is within a fixed range.  For example, by entering a 1.00, all</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>price variances within $1.00 of the plant price are removed.  This</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>includes both positive and negative variances to the plant price.  If</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>the user wishes to removes prices where the price variance is within 5%,</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE> choose the PRICE VARIANCE PERCENT +- and enter 5 in the field next to</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>it.  The user may opt to view the variances weighted by STOCK VARIANCE</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>(i.e. average price * quantity).  The STOCK VARIANCE VALUE +- and STOCK</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>VARIANCE PERCENT +- radio buttons provide these options.</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDFORMAT>AS</TDFORMAT>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDFORMAT>U2</TDFORMAT>
       <TDLINE>&amp;SELECTION&amp;</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDFORMAT>AS</TDFORMAT>
       <TDLINE>There are no mandatory fields on the selection screen.  The GENERAL</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>SEARCH CRITERIA  allows the user to choose the materials.</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDFORMAT>U2</TDFORMAT>
       <TDLINE>&amp;STANDARD_VARIANTS&amp;</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDFORMAT>AS</TDFORMAT>
       <TDLINE>The user may summarize the data.  All original data is at the plant</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>level.  This can be summarized up to the company level and further</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>summarized to a material level (not recommended).  Plant specific fields</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>will be suppressed when summarizing at the Company Code or Material</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>levels.  The company code column will disappear if the report is</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>summarized to the material level.  In rare instances, pricing units may</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>not match.  If that occurs, the users will see ??????</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDFORMAT>U2</TDFORMAT>
       <TDLINE>&amp;OUTPUT&amp;</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDFORMAT>AS</TDFORMAT>
       <TDLINE>The output can be either an ALV report (default) or sent to an EXCEL</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDLINE>file.</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDFORMAT>U1</TDFORMAT>
       <TDLINE>&amp;ACTIVITIES&amp;</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDFORMAT>AS</TDFORMAT>
       <TDLINE>The program makes ZMMMI015 obsolete.</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDFORMAT>U1</TDFORMAT>
       <TDLINE>&amp;EXAMPLE&amp;</TDLINE>
      </TLINE>
      <TLINE>
       <TDFORMAT>AS</TDFORMAT>
      </TLINE>
     </LINES>
